General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) Located immediately above the place on the contract where the consumer's
2 signature is required, the following in 12-point bold font:
3 "Do not sign this contract before you have read it completely or if it
4 contains any blank spaces. You are entitled to a completely filled-in copy of
5 the contract. Before you sign this contract, you should obtain the advice of an
6 attorney. Depending on the circumstances, you may want to consult a tax,
7 public or private benefits planning, or financial professional. You
8 acknowledge that your attorney in the legal claim is not obligated to provide
9 any tax, public or private benefit planning, or financial advice regarding this
10 transaction.
11 You shall not use funds from this transaction to pay attorneys' fees or costs
12 related to the litigation of your claim."
13 (5) A requirement that a copy of the executed consumer legal funding contract
14 shall promptly be delivered to the consumer's attorney upon request.
15 (6) A statement of the maximum total amount to be assigned by the consumer to
16 the consumer legal funding company, including the funded amount and all
17 charges.
18 (e) Each contract shall include consumer disclosures on the first two pages, to the extent
19 possible. The consumer disclosures shall include all of the following:
20 (1) Notification that some or all of the funded amount may be taxable.
21 (2) A description of the consumer's right of rescission.
22 (3) The total funded amount provided to the consumer under the contract.
23 (4) An itemization of charges.
24 (5) The total amount due from the consumer, in six-month intervals for 36
25 months, including all charges.
26 (6) A statement that no additional charges may accrue 36 months after execution
27 of the consumer legal funding contract.
28 (7) A statement that there are no payments owed by the consumer other than what
29 is disclosed on the disclosure form.
30 (8) In the event the consumer seeks more than one consumer legal funding
31 contract, a disclosure providing the cumulative amount due from the consumer
32 for all transactions, including charges under all contracts, if repayment is made
33 any time after the contracts are executed.
34 (9) A statement that the company has no influence over any aspect of the
35 consumer's legal claim or any settlement or resolution of the consumer's legal
36 claim and that all decisions related to the consumer's legal claim remain solely
37 with the consumer and the consumer's attorney.
38 (10) A statement that if there is no recovery of any money from the consumer's
39 legal claim, the consumer has no further financial obligation to the company
40 unless the consumer committed fraud against the consumer legal funding
41 company.
42 (11) A statement that, if the net proceeds of the claim are insufficient to repay the
43 consumer's financial obligation to the company, defined as the complete
44 funded amount and charges, the consumer is not responsible to the company
45 for any amount in excess of the net proceeds.
46 (f) The consumer legal funding contract shall contain a written acknowledgement by the
47 attorney retained by the consumer for the legal claim that attests to the following:
48 (1) To the best of the attorney's knowledge, the funded amounts and any charges
49 relating to the consumer legal funding transaction have been disclosed to the
50 consumer.
House Bill 925-Third Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) The attorney is being paid pursuant to a separate written fee agreement
2 between the consumer and the attorney, and the consumer legal funding
3 company is not a party to that agreement.
4 (3) Gross proceeds of the legal claim shall be deposited into the client trust
5 account of the attorney or a settlement fund established to receive the gross
6 proceeds of the legal claim on behalf of the consumer.
7 (4) The attorney shall comply with the written irrevocable instructions of the
8 consumer with regard to the consumer legal funding transaction.
9 (5) The attorney is obligated to disburse proceeds from the legal claim and pay
10 the funded amount and charges due per the terms of the consumer legal
11 funding contract.
12 (6) Only liens related to the legal claim, including attorney liens, Medicare,
13 Veterans Affairs, TriCare, Medicaid, State Employees Health Plan, ERISA
14 contractual rights of recovery, valid health care provider liens, or other
15 statutory liens, take priority over any contractual lien of the consumer legal
16 funding company. All other liens take priority by operation of law.
17 (7) The attorney for the legal claim is not obligated to provide any tax, public or
18 private benefit planning, or financial advice regarding the consumer legal
19 funding transaction.
20 (g) The failure of the attorney retained by the consumer for the legal claim to provide
21 written attestation as required by this section renders the contract null and void.
22 (h) A consumer legal funding contract remains valid and enforceable in the event that,
23 subsequent to execution, a consumer moves to substitute counsel or pursues a legal claim pro se.
24 (i) A consumer legal funding contract that intentionally violates this section is null and
25 void, and no person has a right to collect, attempt to collect, receive, or retain any funded amount
26 or charges related to the consumer legal funding.
27 "§ 66-531. Nonrecourse obligation; authorized charges.
28 (a) If a consumer obtains no recovery from the consumer's legal claim, the consumer is
29 not required to repay a consumer legal funding company unless the consumer committed fraud
30 against the consumer legal funding company. If the net proceeds of the claim are insufficient to
31 repay the consumer's financial obligation to the company, defined as the complete funded amount
32 plus charges authorized by this section, the consumer is not responsible to the company for any
33 amount in excess of the net proceeds.
34 (b) The contracted amount to be paid to the consumer legal funding company shall be a
35 predetermined amount based upon intervals of time from the funding date through the resolution
36 date and shall not be determined as a percentage of the recovery from the legal claim.
37 (c) Upon written request from the consumer or the consumer's attorney, the consumer
38 legal funding company shall reduce charges to a maximum of twenty-five percent (25%) of the
39 gross proceeds from the legal claim. Any such written request must include an attestation as to
40 the final amount of the gross proceeds from the legal claim.
41 (d) No charges shall accrue on a consumer legal funding transaction more than 36 months
42 after execution of the consumer legal funding contract. A consumer legal funding company,
43 however, may assess charges on any additional funding, whether by amendment to the consumer
44 legal funding contract or by execution of a new consumer legal funding contract, for 36 months
45 after the provision of the additional funding.
46 "§ 66-532. Prohibited acts by a consumer legal funding company.
47 (a) A consumer legal funding company shall not do any of the following:
48 (1) Pay or offer to pay commissions, referral fees, or any other form of
49 consideration to any attorney, law firm, health care provider, or an employee
50 of a law firm or health care provider for referring a consumer to the company.
Page 4 House Bill 925-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) Accept any commissions, referral fees, or any other form of consideration
2 from any attorney, law firm, health care provider, or an employee of a law
3 firm or health care provider.
4 (3) Refer, in furtherance of the initial legal funding, a consumer or potential
5 consumer to an attorney, law firm, health care provider, or an employee of a
6 law firm or health care provider; however, a consumer legal funding company
7 may direct a consumer or potential consumer to a local or state bar association
8 referral service or bona fide nonprofit legal aid organization.
9 (4) Advertise false or misleading information regarding its products or services.
10 (5) Receive any right to make any decisions with respect to or attempt to influence
11 a decision relating to the conduct, settlement, or resolution of the consumer's
12 legal claim. The right to make these decisions remains solely with the
13 consumer and the consumer's attorney.
14 (6) Knowingly pay or offer to pay for case expenses, including court costs, filing
15 fees, or attorneys' fees, either during or after the resolution of the legal claim.
16 (7) Fail to promptly provide copies of contract documents to the consumer or the
17 consumer's attorney upon request.
18 (8) Provide legal advice to the consumer regarding the consumer legal funding
19 transaction or the underlying legal claim.
20 (9) Report a consumer to a credit reporting agency if insufficient funds remain
21 from the net proceeds to repay the company unless the consumer has
22 committed fraud against the consumer legal funding company.
23 (10) Knowingly provide funding to a consumer who has previously assigned or
24 sold a portion of the consumer's right to proceeds from the consumer's legal
25 claim without first purchasing a prior unsatisfied consumer legal funding
26 company's entire funded amount and contracted charges, unless a lesser
27 amount is otherwise expressly agreed to in writing by the consumer legal
28 funding companies. Multiple consumer legal funding companies, however,
29 may agree to contemporaneously provide funding to a consumer so long as
30 the consumer and the consumer's attorney consent to the agreement in writing.
31 (11) Collect from a consumer any fees or charges not authorized under this Article.
32 (12) Sell a contract in whole or in part to a third party. However, if the consumer
33 legal funding company or their affiliate company retains responsibility for
34 collecting payment, administering, and otherwise enforcing the consumer
35 legal funding contract, this prohibition does not apply to any of the following:
36 a. An assignment to a wholly owned subsidiary of the consumer legal
37 funding company.
38 b. An assignment to an affiliate of the consumer legal funding company
39 that is under common control.
40 c. The granting of a security interest under Article 9 of Chapter 25 of the
41 General Statutes or as otherwise permitted by law.
42 (13) Knowingly offering or colluding to provide funding as an inducement to a
43 consumer who is presently represented by counsel to terminate that
44 engagement and engage such lawyer or law firm to represent them in the same
45 matter. Any consumer legal funding contract entered into in violation of this
46 paragraph shall be void ab initio.
47 (14) Collude with or knowingly assist a lawyer or law firm that is inducing or
48 intends to induce a consumer to bring a claim that the company knows or has
49 reason to know is fabricated or otherwise not brought in good faith. Any
50 consumer legal funding contract entered into in violation of this subdivision
51 shall be void ab initio.
