1 (15) Accepting any funds from a foreign government or foreign non-government
2 person identified as a foreign adversary in 15 C.F.R. § 791.4, including any
3 agent or entity affiliated with such foreign adversary.
4 (b) Notwithstanding the restrictions contained in this section, a consumer legal funding
5 company discontinuing its consumer legal funding operations in the State may sell its remaining
6 consumer legal funding receivables to another consumer legal funding company operating in the
7 State pursuant to this Article. The company purchasing the receivables shall notify the consumers
8 and their attorneys of record of the sale and new payment instructions within 30 days of the
9 purchase.
10 "§ 66-533. Enforcement.
11 (a) The Attorney General, upon a finding that a consumer legal funding company has
12 willfully violated the provisions of this Article after notice and opportunity for hearing may
13 assess upon such consumer legal funding company a civil penalty not to exceed ten thousand
14 dollars ($10,000) per violation.
15 (b) In addition to any civil penalty assessed pursuant to subsection (a) of this section, the
16 consumer legal funding company shall not recover the funded amount or any charges under the
17 consumer legal funding contract.
18 (c) The clear proceeds of any penalty assessed pursuant to this section shall be remitted
19 to the Civil Penalty and Forfeiture Fund in accordance with G.S. 115C-457.2.
20 (d) All civil penalties assessed pursuant to this section shall be due and payable within
21 10 days after written notice of assessment is served on the person. If a civil penalty is not paid
22 within the applicable time period, the Attorney General may file a certified copy of the notice of
23 assessment with the clerk of the district court in the county where the violation occurred. The
24 notice of assessment shall be enforced in the same manner as a judgment of the district court.
25 (e) Any action by the Attorney General pursuant to this section shall be subject to judicial
26 review in the General Court of Justice.
27 "§ 66-534. Attorney prohibitions.
28 (a) An attorney retained by a consumer for a legal claim, or that attorney's immediate
29 family member, shall not have a financial interest in the consumer legal funding company
30 offering consumer legal funding to the consumer. Additionally, any attorney who has referred
31 the consumer to the consumer's retained attorney shall not have a financial interest in the
32 consumer legal funding company offering consumer legal funding to the consumer.
33 (b) An attorney retained by a consumer for a legal claim shall not execute a consumer
34 legal funding contract on behalf of the consumer.
35 (c) An attorney who violates this section shall be subject to discipline by the State Bar of
36 North Carolina.
37 "§ 66-535. Effect of communication on privileges.
38 Communications between a consumer's attorney and a consumer legal funding company
39 necessary to ascertain the status of a legal claim or a legal claim's expected value shall not be
40 discoverable by a party with whom the claim is filed or against whom the claim is asserted. This
41 section does not limit, waive, or abrogate the scope or nature of any statutory or common-law
42 privilege, including the work-product doctrine and the attorney-client privilege.
43 "§ 66-536. Disclosure of consumer legal funding transactions.
44 (a) Within 30 calendar days of receipt of a written request, a consumer shall disclose to
45 any party to a legal claim whether the consumer has entered into a consumer legal funding
46 transaction.
47 (b) If a consumer enters into a consumer legal funding transaction after responding to a
48 request pursuant to subsection (a) of this section, the consumer shall disclose this fact to the
49 requesting person within 30 calendar days after the consumer entered into the transaction.
50 "§ 66-537. Discovery and admission of consumer legal funding contracts.
Page 6 House Bill 925-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a) Discovery. – Consumer legal funding contracts are presumed to be discoverable in a
2 civil action, notwithstanding any agreement or provision with respect to confidentiality. A
3 consumer may seek to rebut this presumption.
4 (b) Admission. – Consumer legal funding transactions disclosed pursuant to G.S. 66-536
5 and consumer legal funding contracts discovered pursuant to subsection (a) of this section are
6 presumed to be inadmissible as evidence. A party may seek to rebut this presumption."
7 SECTION 2. If any provision of this act or its application to any person or
8 circumstance is held invalid, the invalidity does not affect other provisions or applications of this
9 act that can be given effect without the invalid provision or application and, to this end, the
10 provisions of this act are severable.
11 SECTION 3. The Secretary of State shall develop forms to implement G.S. 66-529,
12 as enacted by this act.
13 SECTION 4. This act becomes effective October 1, 2026, and applies to violations
14 occurring on or after that date.
